01:02:52.790 --> 01:02:56.960
[more chuckling]
And I thought that was brilliant.

01:02:56.960 --> 01:02:58.220
[laughter]

01:02:58.220 --> 01:03:06.950
I thought this is, in a way, in my wildest
dreams I'm John the Baptist.

01:03:06.950 --> 01:03:07.950
[laughter]

01:03:07.950 --> 01:03:09.440
&gt;&gt;Paul Woolmington: Chris.

01:03:09.440 --> 01:03:16.750
&gt;&gt;Chris Di Cesare: One thing, I guess who
I'm really impressed by. One thing on YouTube

01:03:16.750 --> 01:03:25.349
that I'm like, amazed by is that where the
top partners on YouTube, these guys who create

01:03:25.349 --> 01:03:32.040
these web series are amazing to me because
not only do they have to create the content,

01:03:32.040 --> 01:03:33.040
they have to market the content.

01:03:33.040 --> 01:03:38.700
They have to basically become this A-B-C,
but they're sitting in their bedroom creating

01:03:38.700 --> 01:03:42.870
all this. [Paul Woolmington chuckles] And
some of them now are making big bucks. I mean,

01:03:42.870 --> 01:03:48.330
so just this and it's the same thing, they
probably have no idea when they started that

01:03:48.330 --> 01:03:52.130
that was they were gonna become a network
unto themselves.

01:03:52.130 --> 01:03:57.260
But people now that know that they not only
create the content, but how to foster and

01:03:57.260 --> 01:03:59.960
grow a community, I'm just amazed by.

01:03:59.960 --> 01:04:01.410
&gt;&gt;Paul Woolmington: Susan.

01:04:01.410 --> 01:04:08.490
&gt;&gt;Susan Bonds: So, just to echo what these
guys are saying, I think for me, what is inspiring

01:04:08.490 --> 01:04:15.500
to me is actually seeing people go after these
sacred silos and saying, "Well, I'm not going

01:04:15.500 --> 01:04:23.589
to do it like that. I'm going to do it differently."
And I mean, I look at, I think they do quality

01:04:23.589 --> 01:04:27.820
programming at HBO, but they're also thinking
about what is it people really want.

01:04:27.820 --> 01:04:33.140
And they're launching things that give people
access to content that is counterintuitive.

01:04:33.140 --> 01:04:37.310
You're like, "Well, if we give them access
to next week's episode this week, then who's

01:04:37.310 --> 01:04:41.820
gonna come back and watch it next week?" But
in fact, they're just feeding the frenzy because

01:04:41.820 --> 01:04:46.480
people feel like, "Oh. We are somehow participating
in all this quality entertainment that's coming

01:04:46.480 --> 01:04:47.480
out."

01:04:47.480 --> 01:04:51.369
But I think the thing I'm really looking for
is what we're saying, which is someone who

01:04:51.369 --> 01:04:57.340
is not in any way, no one foot, toe, finger,
whatever, stuck to the notion of traditional

01:04:57.340 --> 01:04:59.180
media models. They're just like, 'Well, we're
just gonna do it like this." And then everyone's

01:04:59.180 --> 01:05:03.940
gonna look and go, "Oh yeah. We were stuck
over here so we couldn't see that, but now

01:05:03.940 --> 01:05:06.369
that we see it, we can all go for that."

01:05:06.369 --> 01:05:15.660
&gt;&gt;Ted Hope: There's a lot of great work that's
being done out there that inspires me on a

01:05:15.660 --> 01:05:23.839
daily basis. The thing that I struggle with
most and what I'm always looking for is the

01:05:23.839 --> 01:05:29.190
folks who are willing to slow down to try
to tell a big story that in the independent

01:05:29.190 --> 01:05:34.109
world, people write this script and then they
think they can make a movie right away.

01:05:34.109 --> 01:05:39.619
I've been working for about three years with
a filmmaker named Lance Wiler, who is in some

01:05:39.619 --> 01:05:42.560
ways the most famous filmmaker that nobody
knows. But we've been doing a transmedia build,

01:05:42.560 --> 01:05:50.390
working a long time on the script to make
sure that the story element of it truly holds

01:05:50.390 --> 01:06:01.359
up and has enough openings in it at the same
time that it can last for a much bigger world.

01:06:01.359 --> 01:06:07.390
And along the way, he's been willing to do
what he calls a lot of "story R&amp;D," things

01:06:07.390 --> 01:06:17.330
that he, whether they're events or installations
or films or apps. Putting things out into

01:06:17.330 --> 01:06:24.830
the community, letting people play with it.
Some of this, Frank touches in his book, emergent

01:06:24.830 --> 01:06:33.730
storytelling, emergent game play, really not
needing to succeed in making a masterwork

01:06:33.730 --> 01:06:38.270
of art at an early stage, but willing to let,
let's see how people play with it and try

01:06:38.270 --> 01:06:39.730
to adapt that.

01:06:39.730 --> 01:06:45.630
But really the part that for all of this tons
of visionary whatever he did at age 15, it

01:06:45.630 --> 01:06:54.560
didn't come my way in pill form. I really
wish that I had gotten hold of, but the thing

01:06:54.560 --> 01:07:01.700
that's really most impressive to me is the
willingness to, like, I don't have to produce

01:07:01.700 --> 01:07:02.780
it overnight. I don't need to be proclaimed
a genius.

01:07:02.780 --> 01:07:09.140
I don't need to win the Sundance Film Festival
and get picked up. I can actually try to manage

01:07:09.140 --> 01:07:18.589
something. I'm gonna engage a lot of people
and I'm gonna depend on the crowd for us to

01:07:18.589 --> 01:07:20.869
try to get it right. That to me is very inspiring.

01:07:20.869 --> 01:07:22.740
&gt;&gt;Paul Woolmington: Yeah. No, that's great.
My only comment would be to celebrate the

01:07:22.740 --> 01:07:27.130
brilliant misfits that sort of--. That's what
we try and say at Naked is we're always trying

01:07:27.130 --> 01:07:31.450
to hire the brilliant misfits. Clearly, everyone
wants brilliant people, but--

01:07:31.450 --> 01:07:33.230
&gt;&gt;Ted Hope: Good listing.

01:07:33.230 --> 01:07:34.230
[laughter]

01:07:34.230 --> 01:07:38.619
&gt;&gt;Paul Woolmington: Yeah, but anyway. That's
a nice segue because I know that there's,

01:07:38.619 --> 01:07:42.550
I think, some friends of Google in the audience
and certainly I think there's a number of

01:07:42.550 --> 01:07:44.960
people from, I think, brilliant misfits in
the audience 'cause I've had the pleasure

01:07:44.960 --> 01:07:51.160
of working with the Creative Lab and some
of the amazing people are working there.

01:07:51.160 --> 01:07:59.021
So, I'd love to throw it open to the audience
