three, or even perhaps a four year period?

01:11:43.440 --> 01:11:47.749
&gt;&gt;Ted Hope: Yeah, I wish I knew that answer.

01:11:47.749 --> 01:11:48.749
[laughter]

01:11:48.749 --> 01:11:52.409
&gt;&gt;Susan Bonds: Did you get their telephone
number?

01:11:52.409 --> 01:11:55.777
&gt;&gt;Ted Hope: It's hard. Particularly in the
tech world, there's always ways to raise funds

01:11:55.777 --> 01:11:56.777
for experiment and innovation. And it's a
lot harder in the content business for that.

01:11:56.777 --> 01:11:57.777
I think that part of the problem we're also
relying on a financial model that is, again,

01:11:57.777 --> 01:11:58.777
based on generally the feature film dominance
or ad-based television.

01:11:58.777 --> 01:11:59.777
So, how do we start to move to something else?
'Cause certainly if I can bring a community

01:11:59.777 --> 01:12:00.777
together that stays together over a long period
of time and all I'm doing is selling them

01:12:00.777 --> 01:12:01.777
a ticket, or a download, to a movie, I'm not
a very good businessperson. If I can find

01:12:01.777 --> 01:12:02.777
people's liked interests I should be able
to drive a fair amount of different forms

01:12:02.777 --> 01:12:03.777
of commerce through that community.

01:12:03.777 --> 01:12:04.777
I think that part of the problem is we're
probably still all looking at old revenue

01:12:04.777 --> 01:12:05.777
models for it as opposed to something that's
more of a new revenue model. If we're bringing

01:12:05.777 --> 01:12:06.777
people together and they're responding to
the things that we like, they're revealing

01:12:06.777 --> 01:12:07.777
a great deal of data that's useful to a lot
of different people, too.

01:12:07.777 --> 01:12:08.777
&gt;&gt;Paul Woolmington: Chris.

01:12:08.777 --> 01:12:09.777
&gt;&gt;Susan Bonds: I actually think, too, that
this is an opportunity because you don't have

01:12:09.777 --> 01:12:10.777
to open a movie on opening weekend to get
